@node Buffer protection
@section Buffer protection

@vindex claude-code-extras-protect-buffers
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-protect-buffers} controls whether killing a Claude Code buffer requires confirmation. When set to non-@code{nil} (the default), any attempt to kill a buffer with a live Claude process triggers a @samp{yes-or-no-p} prompt. This prevents accidental loss of an active session. When the process has already exited (e.g. via the @samp{/exit} command inside Claude), the prompt is skipped.

The default value is @code{t}. Set it to @code{nil} if you prefer to kill Claude buffers without confirmation.

@node Logging options
@section Logging options

@vindex claude-code-extras-log-directory
@vindex claude-code-extras-log-interval
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-log-directory} specifies the directory where conversation logs are saved. Each Claude session gets its own timestamped log file. The default value is the @samp{claude-logs} subdirectory under @code{paths-dir-notes} (@ref{Overview}). You would change this if you want logs stored elsewhere in your filesystem.

The user option @code{claude-code-extras-log-interval} controls how often (in seconds) the buffer contents are saved to disk. The default is 30, meaning the log file is updated every 30 seconds while the session is active. Lower values provide more granular recovery in case of a crash; higher values reduce disk I/O@.

@node Terminal rendering
@section Terminal rendering

@vindex claude-code-extras-sigwinch-delay
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-sigwinch-delay} specifies the delay (in seconds) before sending a @samp{SIGWINCH} signal to the Claude process after startup. This works around a race condition where the TUI queries terminal dimensions before the Eat terminal window is fully laid out, resulting in a garbled banner. The default value is @samp{0.5}. Increase it if you still see rendering artifacts on slower machines.

@node Alert options
@section Alert options

@vindex claude-code-extras-alert-on-ready
@vindex claude-code-extras-alert-style
@vindex claude-code-extras-alert-sound
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-alert-on-ready} controls whether the user is notified when Claude finishes responding. The default is @code{nil} (no alerts). Toggle it interactively with @code{claude-code-extras-toggle-alert} (@ref{Toggling alerts}).

The user option @code{claude-code-extras-alert-style} determines the type of notification. It accepts one of three values: @code{visual} (an OS notification via the @samp{alert} package), @code{sound} (an audio alert), or @code{both} (the default when alerts are enabled). This option only takes effect when @code{claude-code-extras-alert-on-ready} is non-@code{nil}.

The user option @code{claude-code-extras-alert-sound} specifies the path to the sound file played for audible alerts. The default is @samp{/System/Library/Sounds/Glass.aiff}, a macOS system sound. Change this to any audio file that @samp{afplay} can handle.

@node Status polling options
@section Status polling options

@vindex claude-code-extras-status-interval
The user option @code{claude-code-extras-status-interval} sets the polling frequency (in seconds) for reading the status JSON file. The default is 5. Lower values give more responsive modeline updates; higher values reduce filesystem polling overhead.

